canonical example take say simple naive bayes inference про который спрашивали if you relax the assumption that both prior and joint distributions should be in exponential family then you re stuck cause your posterior distribution is then given by some intractable integral and the only thing that can save you here is mcmc methods

если так на пальцах объяснить есть 3 подхода в изучении control theory
1 через laplace transform shift from time domain to frequency domain and use complex analysis in frequency domain это самый сложный и уже устаревший подход
2 стандартный инженерный подход через линейную алгебру

3 математический геометрический подход здесь главная идея что all key properties in linear control theory such as controllability observability detectability stabilizability solutions of matrix differential equations invariant subspaces output regulatedness etc are all invariant under coordinate transformations so instead of using matrices you can go for coordinate free representation of all these notions using things like groups of linear transformations rings of polynomials quotient subspaces etc и это имеет свои дивиденды очень много проблем которые решать линейной алгеброй очень сложно и требует каких то за уши натянутых преобразований и разложений матриц которые если ты не гений то заметить просто нереально but if you recast the same problem into coordinate free geometric framework it becomes almost trivial this allows you to throw out the matrices unless you wanna do the computation

zhenisbek s answer is great and has a practical value i ll try to add to that my stream of thoughts they have zero practical utility but imo helps to build the geometric intuition around neural nets nns instead of burying insight in dg terminology i ll give an example in euclidean space ℝ³ and then generalize it consider first a smooth i e differentiable curve and a smooth surface in ℝ³ in the language of dg a smooth curve is diffeomorphic to line i e 1d space and a smooth surface is diffeomorphic to plane i e 2d space this is a fancy way of saying that if you zoom in close enough on each of them a smooth curve will locally start looking like a straight line and a smooth surface will locally start looking like a plane both smooth curve and smooth surface are just examples of what in dg is called differentiable manifolds in this case a curve is said to be a manifold of dimension 1 and plane is said to be a manifold of dimension 2 corresponding to the dimensionality of their diffeomorphic spaces so manifolds generalize the notions of curve and surface to dimensions higher than 2 though we cannot visualize them anymore and to spaces that are not necessarily euclidean in addition to dimensionality differentiable manifolds are characterized by the notion of curvature this essentially indicates how nonlinear a manifold is or in other words how closely you have to zoom in before regions of a manifold will start looking flat to you with this we are ready to attack yeldos question note that implicit assumption behind the nn model trained by backprop is that the data is sampled with some noise from some differentiable manifold and the goal is to learn the embedding of this manifold in a metric space we know that each neuron mathematically is just a differentiable function and adding a layer corresponds to composing functions in the new layer with the ones in it s preceding layer in light of this it is obvious that adding depth i e increasing the number of function compositions in output layer increases the curvature of the manifold we are trying to learn i d like to say that adding width increases dimensionality of the manifold but it is not entirely true since the dimension of the metric space where the manifold is to be embedded is actually determined by the number of weights connections in nn so both depth and width contribute here this has the following implication if the manifold you are trying to learn is n dimensional you ll never be able to embed it i e train it well roughly speaking unless you have at least n connections there is simply not enough room in fact more connections may be necessary think of a curve how many dimensions it requires for embedding so often adding width is preferred to adding depth when only trying to achieve a certain number of connections since computation overhead caused by the addition of width can be parallelized but for depth this is not the case

high condition number is said to be ill conditioned where high condition number means sensitive number
ok this counter example should help you to see that condition number is not about big elements in matrix

consider ai where i is n n identity matrix and a is non zero scalar choose it as big as you want then we have κ ai ai 1 ai 1 a i 1 a i 1 for any choice of scalar a so for large a ai will have large elements but as you see this does not affect its condition number

maybe this geometric image will help to understand condition number every n n non singular matrix can be visualized as n dimensional ellipsoid where directions of axes of the ellipsoid are given by the direction of its eigenvectors and the length of an 𝑖th axis is given by 1 λᵢ where λᵢ is the 𝑖th eigenvalue more regular shape of this ellipsoid i e if it is more like a sphere will give lower condition number and more irregular i e sausage like shape will give higher condition number
so condition number of a is proportional to the ratio of the absolute values of the largest in magnitude eigenvalue of a to the smallest in magnitude eigenvalue of a

now why do we care about this ratio because if a is ill conditioned then even small perturbations in v will result in relatively large changes in av which can be problematic when doing computations with computer
